      id: 'a26',
      question: 'What is the Iltifat (shift of address) and what are its types?',
      answer: 'Iltifat is a rhetorical device where the speaker shifts from one grammatical person to another without logical necessity — moving from first to second to third person or vice versa. Its purpose is to maintain the listener\'s attention, express emotional intensity, or achieve stylistic variation. Types: (1) From third to second person: وَهُوَ الَّذِي أَرْسَلَ الرِّيَاحَ... وَأَنزَلْنَا مِنَ السَّمَاءِ (He who sends winds... and We sent down from the sky — shift from third to first). (2) From second to third person. (3) From first to second. Al-Zamakhshari in Al-Kashshaf and al-Jurjani in Dala\'il al-Ijaz analyzed Iltifat extensively in the Quran. The shift from أَنعَمتَ (You bestowed) in al-Fatihah to المَغضُوبِ عَلَيهِم (those who earned anger) is cited as a subtle shift away from attributing anger directly to Allah as a mark of divine courtesy (adab).',
