      answer: 'Al-Kitab (The Book) by Abu Bishr Amr ibn Uthman ibn Qanbar Sibawayh (d. approx. 180 AH) is the first and most comprehensive work in Arabic grammatical theory. Sibawayh was a Persian who became the greatest Arab grammarian, studying under al-Khalil ibn Ahmad al-Farahidi (who also invented Arabic prosody and the Arabic dictionary). Al-Kitab documents the Arabic language as spoken by the Bedouins of the Arabian Peninsula and establishes the theoretical framework of irab, bina, the three parts of speech, and the concepts of amil (governing factor) and mamul (governed element). Despite never naming the book himself, it became known simply as Al-Kitab — The Book. It is the reference point for all subsequent grammarians. Al-Akhfash al-Awsat (Sibawayh\'s student) was the first to teach it publicly.',
