      id: 'a34',
      question: 'What is the Mamnu min al-Sarf (diptote) and what are its conditions?',
      answer: 'A Mamnu min al-Sarf (diptote) is a noun that: (1) does not accept tanwin; (2) takes fathah instead of kasrah in the jarr state. A noun becomes mamnu from sarf when it combines two of the following causes, or has one cause that counts double: Causes: (1) Femininity marker (ta marbuta or alif): حَمْرَاءُ، فَاطِمَةُ. (2) Being a foreign proper noun: إِبْرَاهِيمُ، إِسْمَاعِيلُ. (3) Being on the pattern afal: أَحْمَرُ، أَكْبَرُ. (4) Being a compound proper noun: بَعْلَبَكُّ. (5) Added alif and nun: عُثْمَانُ، رَمَضَانُ. (6) Being on the pattern of a verb: أَحْمَدُ، يَزِيدُ. (7) Plural of a pattern (plural of abundance): مَسَاجِدُ، دَرَاهِمُ، أَسَاتِذَةُ. Exception: when preceded by al- or in idafah, diptotes revert to full declension with tanwin.',
