      question: 'What is the Kinayah (metonymy) in Arabic rhetoric and how does it differ from Majaz?',
      answer: 'Kinayah is using an expression whose literal meaning is possible but whose intended meaning is something related to it — without an explicit statement of the intended meaning. Example: هُوَ كَثِيرُ الرَّمَادِ (He has much ash) — literally possible, but the intended meaning is "he is generous" (because generous people who cook for guests produce much ash from their fires). The difference from Majaz: in Majaz, a qarinah (contextual indicator) prevents the literal meaning from being intended. In Kinayah, the literal meaning IS still possible and valid — you can intend either the literal or the figurative. This is why rhetoricians say: الكِنَايَةُ أَبْلَغُ مِنَ التَّصْرِيح (Kinayah is more eloquent than explicit statement) — because it conveys the meaning while leaving room for imagination. Three types: kinayah about an attribute, a person, or a relationship.',
