      answer: 'Al-Fil al-Mujarrad (bare verb) consists entirely of root letters with no added letters. Triliteral mujarrad verbs (thulathi mujarrad) have three root letters and follow six vowel patterns: فَعَلَ، فَعِلَ، فَعُلَ (for the madi) and يَفْعُلُ، يَفْعِلُ، يَفْعَلُ (for the mudari). Each madi/mudari combination produces a specific bab (chapter): e.g., نَصَرَ يَنصُرُ (to help — bab nasara), ضَرَبَ يَضرِبُ (to strike — bab daraba), فَتَحَ يَفتَحُ (to open — bab fataha), سَمِعَ يَسمَعُ (to hear — bab samia), حَسُنَ يَحسُنُ (to be good — bab hasuna). Al-Fil al-Mazid (augmented verb) has one or more letters added to the root, creating derived forms (Forms II-X for triliteral, Forms XI-XV for quadriliteral), each adding a semantic nuance to the base meaning.',
