      answer: 'Wasl (connection) means joining two sentences with waw al-atf (conjunctive waw), indicating a relationship between them. Fasl (separation) means not using waw, treating each sentence as independent. The science of knowing when to use wasl and when to use fasl is one of the most difficult in balagha — al-Jurjani called mastering it "the hardest thing in rhetoric." Rules: Fasl is used when: (1) the second sentence is the answer to an implied question raised by the first; (2) the two sentences are so closely related they are like one; (3) one is a clarification (bayan) of the other. Wasl is used when: (1) both sentences share the same grammatical type and semantic purpose; (2) the speaker wants to indicate that both events have equal weight. The opening of Surah al-Baqarah: ذَٰلِكَ الكِتَابُ لَا رَيبَ فِيه — each phrase is fasil from the other for specific rhetorical reasons analyzed by the commentators.',
