      question: 'What are the conditions under which Laysa is used, and how does it differ from Ma al-Hijaziyyah?',
      answer: 'Laysa is a defective verb (one of the kana family) used for negation. It puts its isim in raf and its khabar in nasb: لَيسَ زَيدٌ قَائِمًا (Zayd is not standing). Ma al-Hijaziyyah is a particle (used by Hejazi Arabs) that similarly negates a nominal sentence, putting its isim in raf and khabar in nasb: مَا زَيدٌ قَائِمًا (Zayd is not standing). Key differences: (1) Laysa has no conditions on its khabar beyond normal nasb rules. Ma al-Hijaziyyah has strict conditions: its khabar must not be preceded by illa (if so, the irab is canceled — this is called ilgha), e.g., مَا زَيدٌ إِلَّا قَائِمٌ (Zayd is none but standing — khabar returns to raf). (2) Ma al-Tamimiyyah (used by Najdi Arabs) treats ma as a non-governing particle, leaving both isim and khabar in raf. (3) Laysa is a verb with full conjugation; ma is a particle.',
      source: 'Qatr al-Nada; Mughni al-Labib, Ibn Hisham',
      tags: ['laysa', 'ma al-hijaziyyah', 'advanced', 'nahw'],
