      answer: 'Islamic law developed through four recognized eras: (1) Era of the Prophet (610-632 CE) — revelation and direct prophetic ruling; no juristic disagreement in the technical sense since the Prophet\'s ruling was final. (2) Era of the Companions (632-100 AH approx.) — scholarly ijtihad began; disagreements among Companions produced the first fiqh debates. (3) Era of the Tabiin and early Imams (100-250 AH) — the four madhabs crystallized; Imam Malik, Abu Hanifah, al-Shafii, and Ahmad ibn Hanbal codified systematic fiqh. (4) Era of Taqlid and Codification (250 AH onward) — scholarly activity shifted toward commentary, fatwa within madhabs, and compilation. Contemporary scholars debate whether a fifth era — of renewed ijtihad — is needed given unprecedented modern issues (medical ethics, finance, digital life).',
      source: 'Tarikh al-Tashri al-Islami, Khudari Bek; Al-Madkhal al-Fiqhi al-Amm, Mustafa al-Zarqa',
      tags: ['history of fiqh', 'madhabs', 'intermediate'],
