      question: 'What is the Taarud al-Adillah (conflict of evidences) and how is it resolved?',
      answer: 'Taarud al-Adillah occurs when two valid evidences appear to contradict each other. Resolution methods (in order of priority): (1) Al-Jam wal-tawfiq (reconciliation) — finding a way to apply both evidences by limiting their respective scopes. This is always preferred if possible. (2) Al-Naskh (abrogation) — if one is known to be later, the later abrogates the earlier. Requires established chronology. (3) Al-Tarjih (preferring one over the other) — if reconciliation and naskh are impossible, the stronger evidence is preferred. Criteria of tarjih: clarity of text, strength of chain, conformity with Maqasid, conformity with ijma, etc. (4) Al-Tawaqquف (suspension) — if all of the above fail, the jurist suspends judgment and does not rule. The Hanafi school is known for extensive development of tarjih methodology.',
