      id: 'u27',
      question: 'What is the concept of Azimah and Rukhsah in Islamic law?',
      answer: 'Al-Azimah (primary ruling) is the original ruling applying to all accountable persons in all normal circumstances — the default Sharia position. Al-Rukhsah (concession) is a temporary or situational relaxation of the azimah ruling due to a specific hardship, need, or circumstance. The concession exists alongside the azimah — it does not permanently replace it. Types of rukhsah: (1) Mandatory — you must take it (e.g., eating haram food to survive starvation); (2) Recommended — taking it is recommended (e.g., Qasr during travel); (3) Merely permitted — you may take it but the azimah is better (e.g., breaking the fast while traveling when fasting causes no hardship). The maxim: "Al-asl al-ibahah" (the default for things is permissibility) is related but distinct — it applies to the original status of objects, not to relaxation of rulings.',
