      answer: 'Qiyas al-Awla (also called Mafhum al-Muwafaqah or Fahwa al-Khitab) is extending a ruling to a case that is MORE deserving of that ruling than the original case — not merely equal. It is the strongest form of qiyas. Example: the prohibition of saying "uff" to parents (Quran 17:23) — striking them is even more prohibited by qiyas al-awla since the illah (hurting parents) is more strongly present in striking. Regular qiyas extends a ruling to a case that shares the same illah equally. Qiyas al-Awla is accepted even by the Hanafi school (which otherwise restricts qiyas) and is called Qiyas Jali (obvious analogy) in some classifications. It is so clear that al-Shafii classified it as part of the text\'s own implication rather than separate qiyas.',
