      question: 'What is the difference between Qati and Zanni in usul al-fiqh?',
      answer: 'Qati (definitive/certain) refers to evidences or rulings established with absolute certainty — no valid disagreement is possible. Zanni (probable/speculative) refers to evidences or rulings that carry a high probability but admit valid scholarly disagreement. This distinction operates at two levels: (1) Thabut (establishment of the text) — is the text definitively established? The Quran and Mutawatir Sunnah are qati al-thabut. Ahad Sunnah is zanni al-thabut. (2) Dalalah (indication of the text) — does the text definitively indicate this ruling? A text using clear unambiguous language (nass) is qati al-dalalah. A text using language open to interpretation (zahir, muawwal) is zanni al-dalalah. A ruling is only absolutely certain (qati muтлак) when BOTH its text is qati al-thabut AND qati al-dalalah. Denying a qati ruling is kufr; denying a zanni ruling is scholarly error.',
