      answer: 'Ikhtilaf al-Fuqaha (scholarly disagreement in fiqh) is a natural and inevitable phenomenon in Islamic law, arising from the nature of the sources and the complexity of reality. Legitimate causes of ikhtilaf: (1) Differences in the reach of hadith transmission — a scholar may not have received a certain hadith that another has. (2) Differences in hadith grading — scholars may differ on whether a hadith is sahih or weak. (3) Linguistic ambiguity — the same Arabic word may carry multiple meanings. (4) Differences in usul — whether to use istihsan, maslahah mursalah, or qiyas in a given case. (5) Apparent conflict between two evidences — different tarjih methods lead to different outcomes. Ibn Rushd\'s Bidayat al-Mujtahid documents these causes systematically. Not all ikhtilaf is acceptable: disagreement on qati matters is rejected; disagreement on zanni matters is a mercy.',
