      answer: 'Imam Ahmad ibn Hanbal (d. 241 AH) was primarily a muhaddith (hadith scholar) whose legal methodology is characterized by: (1) Maximum reliance on hadith — he would accept a weak (daif) hadith over qiyas if no stronger evidence existed. (2) Minimal use of qiyas — used only when no text was available. (3) Rejection of speculative rationalism — he strongly opposed using kalam (theological speculation) in fiqh. (4) Following the Companions\' opinions — their views (sahabah) were preferred over qiyas. (5) Using mursal hadith (those with a missing companion link) more liberally than other schools. His position during the Mihna (inquisition) over the createdness of the Quran — where he suffered imprisonment and flogging rather than capitulate — made him the imam of the Ahl al-Sunnah. His school was systematized by later scholars like Ibn Qudamah and Ibn Taymiyyah.',
