      answer: 'The root (al-jidhr / الجِذْر), also called al-maddah (المَادَّة), is the foundational set of usually three consonants encoding a core semantic meaning. All related words derive from this root through insertion of vowels and addition of prefixes/suffixes according to fixed patterns (أَوْزَان / awzan). The root ك-ت-ب (k-t-b) encodes the meaning of writing: كَتَبَ (kataba — he wrote), كِتَابٌ (kitab — book), كَاتِبٌ (katib — writer), مَكْتَبَةٌ (maktabah — library), مَكْتُوبٌ (maktub — written/letter), كِتَابَةٌ (kitabah — the act of writing). The root ع-ل-م (ʿ-l-m) encodes knowledge: عَلِمَ (ʿalima — he knew), عِلْمٌ (ʿilm — knowledge), عَالِمٌ (ʿalim — scholar), مَعْلُومٌ (maʿlum — known), تَعْلِيمٌ (taʿlim — education).',
