      answer: 'Al-Fil al-Lazim (لَازِم — intransitive) does not require a direct object — its action remains with the doer: ذَهَبَ (dhahaba — he went), جَلَسَ (jalasa — he sat), وَقَفَ (waqafa — he stood). It cannot form an ism al-maful directly in the standard way. Al-Fil al-Mutaaddi (مُتَعَدِّي — transitive) takes a direct object (مَفْعُول بِه): ضَرَبَ زَيْدٌ عَمْرًا (Zayd struck Amr). Some verbs can be made transitive by: (1) Changing their bab: سَلِمَ (he was safe — lazim) vs. سَلَّمَ (he greeted/gave safely to — mutaaddi via Form II); (2) Adding a preposition (تَعْدِيَة بِحَرْف): ذَهَبَ بِه (he took him away); (3) Form IV (hamzah): جَلَسَ → أَجْلَسَ (he made him sit). A single verb can also take one object (mutaaddi ilaa mafuul wahid) or two objects (mutaaddi ilaa mafuulayn) like Form IV: أَعْطَى زَيْدٌ عَمْرًا كِتَابًا (Zayd gave Amr a book).',
