      question: 'What is الإِدْغَام (al-idgham — assimilation) in Arabic morphology and what are its conditions?',
      answer: 'Al-Idgham is the merging of two adjacent letters — the first (al-mudgham) absorbs into the second (al-mudgham fih) — producing a doubled (mushaddad) letter. Conditions: (1) the two letters must be identical (idgham mithlain): مَدَّ (madda — from مَدَدَ), رَدَّ (radda — from رَدَدَ); (2) or they can be close in articulation point (idgham mutaqaribayn): ذَلَّ — though this applies more in tajwid than morphology. In morphology, the most common idgham occurs when conjugation brings two identical root letters together: مَدَدَ → when the doer suffix -تُ is added: مَدَدْتُ (no idgham because a sukun would produce two sukuns). But when no suffix forces separation: يَمُدُّ (yamuddu — from يَمْدُدُ). The first letter must be sakin (have sukun) for idgham to occur — if both letters have vowels, idgham is not possible.',
