      answer: 'Al-Ibdal is the substitution of one letter for another due to phonological rules in morphology. Key examples: (1) Waw → Ta in Form VIII (اِفْتَعَلَ) when the first root letter is waw: وَصَلَ → اِتَّصَلَ (not اِوْتَصَلَ); وَعَدَ → اِتَّعَدَ; وَجَدَ → اِتَّجَدَ. (2) Waw → Ya: when waw falls after kasrah or before a kasrah followed by sukun, it converts to ya: مِيزَانٌ (from وَزَنَ — waw after mi becomes ya). (3) Ta → Dal: when the first root letter is dal (د), the ta of Form VIII becomes dal: دَبَرَ → اِدَّبَرَ (from دبر — to manage/reflect). (4) Ta → Ta mushaddad: when the first root letter is ta (ت): تَبَعَ → اِتَّبَعَ. (5) Alif → Waw/Ya: in the ajwaf verb, the middle alif in the past (qala, baa) derives from original waw/ya: قَالَ from ق-و-ل, بَاعَ from ب-ي-ع.',
