      answer: 'Al-Ishtiqaq (derivation) is the process of forming new words from an existing root, preserving the core letters and meaning while adding new semantic nuances through pattern changes. Types of ishtiqaq: (1) الاِشْتِقَاق الصَّغِير (minor derivation) — deriving related words from the same three-letter root: from ك-ت-ب: كَتَبَ، كِتَابٌ، كَاتِبٌ، مَكْتَبٌ. This is the standard sarf process. (2) الاِشْتِقَاق الكَبِير (major derivation) — proposed by Ibn Jinni: two roots sharing the same three consonants in ANY order share a related meaning: قَسَا، قَاسَ، سَقَى — all involve hardness or measurement. (3) الاِشْتِقَاق الأَكْبَر (greatest derivation) — proposed by some scholars: words sharing only two consonants share a meaning (highly controversial). (4) الاِشْتِقَاق النَّحْتِي (blended derivation) — forming new words by blending two words: بَسْمَلَ (to say بِسْمِ اللَّهِ), حَوْقَلَ (to say لَا حَوْلَ وَلَا قُوَّةَ إِلَّا بِاللَّهِ).',
