      answer: 'Al-Iʿlal is the phonological alteration that affects weak letters (waw و, ya ي, alif ا) in Arabic words to ease pronunciation. Types: (1) إِعْلَال بِالقَلْب (by transposition/conversion) — a weak letter changes into another: waw → ya (or vice versa) when conditions require, or waw/ya → alif: قَالَ (from قَوَلَ, the waw becomes alif), بَاعَ (from بَيَعَ, the ya becomes alif). (2) إِعْلَال بِالحَذْف (by deletion) — the weak letter is deleted: يَقُلْ (from يَقُولْ — the waw deleted before sukun in jazm), يَبِعْ (from يَبِيعْ — the ya deleted), ادْعُ (from اُدْعُو — the waw deleted in the command). (3) إِعْلَال بِالتَّسْكِين (by vowellessness/sukun) — converting a voweled weak letter to sukun: يَخَافُ (from يَخْوَفُ — the waw becomes alif due to the fathah before it). These three types interrelate and a single conjugation may involve multiple iʿlal operations simultaneously.',
