      answer: 'Al-Naht is the formation of a new word by blending or compressing a phrase into a single verb or noun, preserving the key letters. Examples: (1) بَسْمَلَ (basmala) — from بِسْمِ اللَّهِ (bismillah — in the name of Allah): يُبَسْمِلُ، بَسْمَلَةٌ. (2) حَوْقَلَ (hawqala) — from لَا حَوْلَ وَلَا قُوَّةَ إِلَّا بِاللَّهِ. (3) حَمْدَلَ (hamdala) — from الحَمْدُ لِلَّهِ. (4) سَبْحَلَ (sabhala) — from سُبْحَانَ اللَّهِ. (5) هَيْلَلَ (haylala) — from لَا إِلَهَ إِلَّا اللَّهُ. (6) طَلْبَقَ (talbaq) — from أَطَالَ اللَّهُ بَقَاءَكَ. This is an ancient Arabic word-formation process documented by Ibn Faris and Ibn Jinni, showing the language\'s capacity for compression without loss of meaning.',
