      answer: 'The principle of istithqal (heaviness — avoiding what is difficult to pronounce) and istikhhaf (lightness — preferring what is easy) is a fundamental driving force behind many phonological changes in Arabic. Core examples of istithqal-driven changes: (1) Diptotes reject tanwin because tanwin on a noun that already has a femininity or foreign marker creates excessive heaviness. (2) Waw drops in Form VIII when the first root is waw: اِوْتَصَلَ is heavy → اِتَّصَلَ (assimilation eases pronunciation). (3) The hollow verb drops its middle letter before a sakin suffix: قُلْتُ (not قُوْلْتُ — two sukuns would be very heavy). (4) The defective verb drops its final letter in jazm: لَمْ يَدْعُ (not لَمْ يَدْعُوْ). (5) The tanwin drops before al-: كِتَابُ الطَّالِبِ (not كِتَابٌ الطَّالِبِ). Understanding this principle allows students to predict many morphological changes rather than memorizing them as arbitrary rules.',
