      answer: 'Al-Shafiyah fi Ilm al-Tasrif (The Sufficient in the Science of Morphology) by Jamal al-Din Abu Amr Uthman ibn al-Hajib al-Maliki (d. 646 AH) is the most studied intermediate-to-advanced text in Arabic morphology. It is a concise treatise covering: verb forms (mujarrad and mazid), noun derivations, phonological changes (iʿlal and ibdal), diminutives, broken plurals, and the diptote. Its most important commentary is Sharh al-Shafiyah by al-Radi al-Istrabadhi (d. 686 AH) — the most encyclopedic commentary on Arabic morphology ever written, analyzing each issue with full grammatical and phonological reasoning. Al-Shafiyah is paired with al-Kafiyah (Ibn al-Hajib\'s syntax text) as a complete morphology-syntax curriculum, and both together with the Alfiyyah of Ibn Malik constitute the core advanced Arabic grammar curriculum in traditional Islamic institutions.',
