      answer: 'Al-Ilhaq is the process of adding letters to a triliteral root to make it resemble a quadriliteral root pattern in conjugation, without the added letters being part of the original root meaning. Purpose: to bring a root into a more regular conjugation pattern. Examples: (1) جَلْبَبَ (jalbaba) — from root ج-ل-ب (3 letters), extended with an extra ba to resemble the quadriliteral فَعْلَلَ pattern: جَلْبَبَ يُجَلْبِبُ (to put on a jilbab). (2) شَمْلَلَ — from ش-م-ل extended to quadriliteral pattern meaning to act quickly. (3) سَلْقَى — from س-ل-ق extended. The ilhaq letter is identified because: (a) removing it returns a valid root; (b) it does not contribute to the core meaning. This is distinguished from genuine quadriliteral roots where all four letters are essential.',
