      answer: 'Al-Tasrif (from صَرَّفَ — to turn/transform) is the science of morphological transformation — changing a single word into all its possible forms to reveal all the information it can convey. For a verb, tasrif covers: (1) Person (شَخْص): third, second, first; (2) Gender (جِنْس): masculine, feminine; (3) Number (عَدَد): singular, dual, plural; (4) Tense (زَمَن): madi, mudari, amr; (5) Voice (بِنَاء): active, passive; (6) Derived forms (مُشْتَقَّات): masdar, ism fail, ism maful, ism makan/zaman, ism alah, sifah mushabbahah. A full tasrif table of a single verb produces 14 madi forms, 14 mudari forms, 12 amr forms, plus all derivatives. The science of sarf is essentially the science of tasrif. Its classical texts (al-Tasrif al-Izzi, Maraah al-Arwah) present verb paradigms (تَصَارِيف) as the primary pedagogical tool.',
