      answer: 'Ism al-Jins is a noun that refers to a species or category collectively without specifying individuals. Ism al-Wahdah is derived from it by adding ta marbuta (ة) to indicate a single unit of that species. Examples: شَجَرٌ (shajar — trees collectively / the species of trees) → شَجَرَةٌ (shajarah — one tree); تَمْرٌ (tamr — dates collectively) → تَمْرَةٌ (tamrah — one date); قَمْحٌ (qamh — wheat) → قَمْحَةٌ (qamhah — one grain of wheat); نَحْلٌ (nahl — bees) → نَحْلَةٌ (nahlah — one bee). Reverse logic: in this case, the ta is NOT added to make a feminine noun — rather, the ta is added to individualize from the generic. The SINGULAR in this category is the one WITH ta, and the PLURAL or GENERIC is without. This is the opposite of the normal pattern where ta indicates feminine and non-ta indicates masculine.',
