      answer: 'Al-Fil al-Sahih is a verb without weak letters (waw, ya, or alif) in its root. The Sahih has three sub-types: (1) Al-Salim (السَّالِم — sound/perfect): no weak letters, no hamzah, no doubling: كَتَبَ، نَصَرَ، جَلَسَ، فَتَحَ. Conjugates completely regularly. (2) Al-Mahmuz (المَهْمُوز — containing hamzah): has hamzah (ء) in one of the three root positions. Hamzah is a strong letter phonologically but causes writing/pronunciation challenges: (a) Mahmuz al-Fa (first position): أَكَلَ (to eat), أَخَذَ (to take), أَمَرَ (to command); (b) Mahmuz al-Ayn (middle position): سَأَلَ (to ask), بَأَسَ (to be harsh); (c) Mahmuz al-Lam (final position): قَرَأَ (to read), بَدَأَ (to begin), مَلَأَ (to fill). (3) Al-Mudaaf (المُضَاعَف — geminate): second and third root letters are identical: ضَرَّ، مَدَّ، رَدَّ. Conjugates with idgham (merging) in some forms.',
