      answer: 'Al-Fil al-Jamid (frozen verb) is a verb that does not have a complete conjugation system — it is "frozen" in one or two forms and cannot be conjugated across all persons, tenses, and genders like a normal verb. Types: (1) Jamid in the madi only — cannot form mudari, amr, or derivatives: نِعْمَ (niʿma — how excellent is!), بِئْسَ (biʾsa — how evil is!), عَسَى (ʿasa — perhaps, in most usages), لَيْسَ (laysa — is not — though some give it fuller conjugation). (2) Jamid in the mudari only — rare. (3) Jamid in the amr only: هَبْ (hab — suppose/grant that) and تَعَلَّمْ (taʿallam — know!/be aware — in the sense of "know that"). Contrast with al-Fil al-Mutasarrif (fully conjugable verb): تَامّ al-Tasarruf (complete: كَتَبَ has all forms) and نَاقِص al-Tasarruf (deficient: كَادَ lacks some forms). The jāmid verb often has a rhetorical or evaluative function rather than a narrative one.',
