      question: 'What is the Mubtada (المُبْتَدَأ) and Khabar (الخَبَر), and what are their conditions?',
      answer: 'The Mubtada is the subject of a nominal sentence — what is being spoken about. The Khabar is the predicate — what is said about the mubtada. Both are in raf by default. Conditions of the Mubtada: (1) must be a marifah (definite) in the default case — a nakirah mubtada requires a specific justification such as being preceded by a negation (مَا رَجُلٌ فِي الدَّارِ), a question (هَلْ رَجُلٌ فِي الدَّارِ?), or when the khabar precedes it. Conditions of the Khabar: (1) must provide new information (faida); (2) must agree with the mubtada in gender and number when it is a single word (mufrad). Types of khabar: (1) Mufrad (single word): زَيْدٌ عَالِمٌ; (2) Jumlah (sentence — verbal or nominal): زَيْدٌ أَبُوهُ قَائِمٌ; (3) Shibh Jumlah (quasi-sentence — prepositional or adverbial phrase): زَيْدٌ فِي الدَّارِ.',
