      answer: 'The Mafuul al-Mutlaq is a verbal noun (masdar) from the same root as the governing verb, placed in nasb. Three functions: (1) Tawkid (emphasis — confirming the action occurred): ضَرَبْتُهُ ضَرْبًا (I struck him — a striking! — confirms the striking happened); (2) Bayan al-Nawʿ (specifying the type/manner): سِرْتُ سَيْرَ الأَبْطَالِ (I walked the walk of heroes — specifies HOW I walked); (3) Bayan al-Adad (specifying the number of occurrences): ضَرَبْتُهُ ضَرْبَتَيْنِ (I struck him twice). The governing verb may be deleted when the mafuul al-mutlaq stands alone, as in Quranic expressions: سُبْحَانَ اللَّهِ (Glory be to Allah — the verb sabbaha is implied), مَعَاذَ اللَّهِ (God forbid!), حَمْدًا لِلَّهِ (praise to Allah).',
