      answer: 'Al-Khabar al-Muqaddam is the predicate placed before the mubtada (against the default order). It is: (1) Permitted (jaʾiz) when the mubtada is definite and the khabar is an indefinite shibh jumlah: فِي الدَّارِ رَجُلٌ (in the house is a man — khabar fronted). (2) Obligatory (wajib) in specific situations: (a) When the mubtada is indefinite and the khabar is a jar wa majrur or zarf — to avoid ambiguity: عِنْدَكَ رَجُلٌ; (b) When the khabar is an interrogative that must come first: كَيْفَ أَنْتَ? (how are you?); (c) When the khabar contains a damir referring to the mubtada: فِي الدَّارِ صَاحِبُهَا (in the house is its owner — fronting required because the damir in sahib refers to al-dar); (d) When the khabar is one of the particles of restriction (إِنَّمَا، مَا...إِلَّا): إِنَّمَا فِي الدَّارِ زَيْدٌ.',
