      answer: 'Kana has two usages: (1) Kana al-Naqisah (deficient) — the most common usage: it is a naaqisa (deficient) verb because it does not form a complete sentence on its own — it needs an isim and khabar: كَانَ زَيْدٌ عَالِمًا (Zayd was a scholar). It puts the isim in raf and khabar in nasb. (2) Kana al-Tammah (complete) — less common: it means "to exist" or "to be/occur" and forms a complete sentence with just a fail (like a regular verb): كَانَ اللَّهُ وَلَمْ يَكُنْ شَيْءٌ غَيْرُهُ (Allah existed and nothing else existed — hadith: kana here = tammah meaning "existed"). In this usage, kana does NOT need a khabar — it is a complete verb with full meaning. This distinction is critical for correct parsing of Quranic and classical texts where كَانَ can shift between the two usages.',
