      answer: 'Al-Isnad is the attribution of a predicate to a subject forming a complete sentence. Two types based on truth value: (1) Al-Isnad al-Khabari (informational isnad) — a sentence that can be evaluated as true or false: زَيْدٌ قَائِمٌ (Zayd is standing — either true or false). It is either true (sadiq) or false (kadhib). This is the basis of Ilm al-Maan (the study of meaningful sentences). (2) Al-Isnad al-Inshaaʾi (performative isnad) — a sentence that performs an action rather than describes one — it cannot be evaluated as true or false: اضْرِبْ زَيْدًا (Strike Zayd! — a command, not a description), هَلْ جَاءَ زَيْدٌ? (Did Zayd come? — a question, not a truth claim), يَا زَيْدُ (O Zayd! — a calling), بِعْتُكَ هَذَا (I sell you this — a contract, true by the utterance itself). This distinction is foundational in Arabic rhetoric (balagha) and Islamic legal theory (distinguishing declarative from performative speech acts).',
