      question: 'What is the Al-Mafuul Maah (المَفْعُول مَعَهُ — companion object) and how does it differ from atf?',
      answer: 'The Mafuul Maah is a noun in nasb following a waw meaning "together with" (waw al-maiyyah), expressing accompaniment — the second noun did not share in the action but merely accompanied the first. Example: سِرْتُ وَالنِّيلَ (I walked along with the Nile — the Nile did not walk; it merely accompanied the walking along its bank). Contrast with Atf: in atf with waw, both nouns participate equally in the verb/predicate: جَاءَ زَيْدٌ وَعَمْرٌو (Zayd and Amr came — both came). Indicators that waw is maiyyah not atf: (1) The second noun logically cannot share the verb (a river cannot walk); (2) A verb or verbal sentence precedes the waw (not a noun); (3) Making the second noun share the verb would be semantically absurd. The mafuul maah must be a noun, not a verb. In the sentence سِرْتُ وَالنِّيلَ — al-Nil is in nasb because it is mafuul maah, not because it participated in the walking.',
