      question: 'What is the Al-Jumlah allati la Mahalla laha min al-Irab (sentences with no irab position)?',
      answer: 'Some sentences in Arabic occupy no irab position — they stand independently and are not governed by any amil. These are: (1) Al-Jumlah al-Ibtidaiyyah (opening sentence) — the main sentence that begins the discourse: زَيْدٌ قَائِمٌ (this whole sentence has no position); (2) Al-Jumlah al-Waqi\'ah Silah lil-Mawsul (the relative clause / silah): جَاءَ الَّذِي ضَرَبْتُهُ — the silah ضَرَبْتُهُ has no irab position (la mahall laha); (3) Al-Jumlah al-Mufassarah (explanatory sentence) — following the particle أَيْ (i.e.) or اَنْ (that) in certain contexts; (4) Al-Jumlah Jawab al-Qasam (response to an oath): وَاللَّهِ لَأَقُومَنَّ — the oath response has no irab position; (5) Al-Jumlah Jawab al-Shart ghair al-Jazim (response to a non-jazm conditional): لَوْ جِئْتَنِي لَأَكْرَمْتُكَ — the jawab of law has no position. This contrasts with sentences that DO have irab positions (mahall): hal sentence (mahall nasb), khabar sentence (mahall raf), etc.',
      source: 'Mughni al-Labib, Ibn Hisham; Sharh al-Tasrih',
      tags: ['la mahall', 'jumlah', 'advanced'],
