      question: 'What is the Tanazu (التَّنَازُع — grammatical competition) in Arabic syntax?',
      answer: 'Tanazu occurs when two or more verbs each seek to govern the same noun. Example: قَامَ وَقَعَدَ زَيْدٌ — both قَامَ (stood) and قَعَدَ (sat) compete for زَيْدٌ as their fail. The Basran and Kufan schools disagree: (1) Basran (majority): the SECOND verb governs the explicit noun (Zayd is the fail of qaʿada); the first verb takes an implicit pronoun: قَامَ هُوَ وَقَعَدَ زَيْدٌ. (2) Kufan: the FIRST verb governs the explicit noun (Zayd is fail of qama); the second takes an implicit pronoun: قَامَ زَيْدٌ وَقَعَدَ هُوَ. Practical implication: if the explicit noun is plural (الرِّجَالُ), the Basran analysis has the first verb take a singular implicit pronoun: قَامَ وَقَعَدَ الرِّجَالُ = قَامَ هُوَ وَقَعَدَ الرِّجَالُ. This phenomenon is frequent in the Quran and classical poetry.',
