      question: 'What is the Mughni al-Labib of Ibn Hisham and why is it considered the most important reference in Arabic syntax?',
      answer: 'Mughni al-Labib an Kutub al-Aarib (The Sufficient for the Intelligent, Away from [the need for] Books on Parsing) by Jamal al-Din Abd Allah ibn Hisham al-Ansari al-Masri (d. 761 AH) is considered the definitive reference work in Arabic syntax. It is organized in two parts: (1) Individual particles — alphabetical treatment of every Arabic particle with all its meanings, uses, and governing rules; (2) General rules — principles of sentence analysis, jumlah theory, irab, and parsing. Its significance: (a) It documents every usage of every particle with Quranic and classical poetic evidence; (b) It resolves long-standing debates between Basran and Kufan schools; (c) It introduced the most systematic treatment of jumlah (sentence) theory in the history of Arabic grammar; (d) Ibn Hisham is considered by many the greatest Arabic grammarian after Sibawayh. His other works (Qatr al-Nada, Awdah al-Masalik, Sharh al-Qatr) form the core curriculum of advanced Arabic grammar study.',
