      answer: 'Naskh in Quranic sciences is the lifting of a prior Sharia ruling by a later Quranic revelation. Types relevant to the Quran: (1) Naskh al-Hukm duna al-Tilawah — the ruling is abrogated but the text remains (most common). Example: the verse requiring 10 suckling sessions for milk-relationship was abrogated in ruling by 5 suckling sessions. (2) Naskh al-Tilawah duna al-Hukm — the text was removed but the ruling remains. Example: the stoning verse (ayat al-rajm) narrated by Umar. (3) Naskh al-Tilawah wal-Hukm — both text and ruling removed. The classical scholars enumerated approximately 20-21 instances of confirmed naskh in the Quran. Important: naskh requires definite chronological evidence — it cannot be established by mere supposition. Ibn al-Jawzi and al-Suyuti wrote detailed works cataloguing the nasikh and mansukh.',
