      answer: 'Al-Tafseer al-Ishari is a form of tafseer that extracts inner or spiritual meanings (isharaat — hints) from Quranic verses beyond their apparent linguistic meanings, practiced particularly by Sufi scholars. Examples: interpreting نُورٌ (light) in Ayat al-Nur (24:35) as referring to the illumination of the heart; interpreting the stages of the hajj as stages of spiritual purification. Scholarly boundaries: (1) Al-Suyuti in al-Itqan and others permit ishari tafseer ONLY if: (a) it does not contradict the zahir (apparent) meaning; (b) there is no claim that this is the only or primary meaning; (c) it is supported by other Islamic evidences; (d) it does not involve rejecting the sharia implications of the verse. (2) Prohibited ishari tafseer: claiming the zahir is only for the masses while the initiated have a hidden (batin) meaning that may contradict the zahir — this is the error of the Batiniyyah (Ismaili Shia and similar groups). Notable ishari tafseer works: Tafseer al-Tustari, Haqaiq al-Tafseer by al-Sulami.',
