      answer: 'Surah al-Ikhlas (Quran 112) consists of four verses and is called al-Ikhlas (Sincerity/Purification — because it purifies Tawhid). The Prophet ﷺ said it equals one-third of the Quran — the scholars explain: the Quran covers three main themes: Tawhid, rulings (ahkam), and accounts of previous nations. Surah al-Ikhlas covers the Tawhid dimension entirely. Tafseer of the four verses: (1) قُلْ هُوَ اللَّهُ أَحَدٌ — "Say: He is Allah, the One." هُوَ is damir al-shaʾn preparing for the supreme statement; أَحَدٌ expresses absolute oneness with no division, no parallel, no equal. (2) اللَّهُ الصَّمَدُ — Allah is al-Samad: the eternally besought — all things need Him; He needs nothing. (3) لَمْ يَلِدْ وَلَمْ يُولَدْ — He neither begets nor was begotten: total negation of the Christian Trinity and Arab polytheist beliefs. (4) وَلَمْ يَكُنْ لَهُ كُفُوًا أَحَدٌ — "And there is none equivalent to Him" — absolute uniqueness.',
