      answer: 'Quran 2:1-2 — Tafseer: (1) الم (Alif-Lam-Mim) — huruf muqattaat: the majority of scholars hold these are among the mutashabih — Allah knows their meaning. The most convincing scholarly view: they are an ijaz challenge — the Quran is composed of the same letters the Arabs use, yet they cannot produce its like. (2) ذَلِكَ الكِتَابُ — "That is the Book" — ذَلِكَ (that — demonstrative pointing to something distant) is used for the Quran revealed from the heavenly realm (the protected tablet — al-Lawh al-Mahfuz), or it points to what the Prophet was told he would receive. Al-Kitab (The Book) — with al- of definiteness indicating this is THE book above all books. (3) لَا رَيبَ فِيهِ — "No doubt in it" — absolute negation: not even the smallest uncertainty in it, in its truth, its divine origin, its transmission. (4) هُدًى لِّلمُتَّقِينَ — "Guidance for the God-conscious (muttaqin)" — huda is in nasb as khabar for an implied mubtada (huwa hudan), or as hal. The restriction of guidance to the muttaqin does not mean it cannot guide others — it means the muttaqin benefit from it most completely.',
