      question: 'What is the Tafseer of Surah al-Rahman and what is the rhetorical significance of the repeated refrain?',
      answer: 'Surah al-Rahman (Quran 55) is a Madani surah of 78 verses containing 31 repetitions of the question: فَبِأَيِّ آلَاءِ رَبِّكُمَا تُكَذِّبَانِ — "So which of the favors of your Lord will you both deny?" The surah is addressed in the dual (kuma — the two of you) throughout — scholars differ: addressed to humans and jinn together, or to the two genders (male and female). The rhetorical significance of the repetition: (1) Each repetition follows a different divine favor — the repetition is not redundant but a fresh challenge after each specific blessing; (2) It is a rhetorical device of Tawkid (emphasis) combined with interrogation (istifham inkari — rhetorical question implying the answer is "none!"); (3) The favors span the celestial (the Quran, the creation of humans from clay, the sun and moon), the terrestrial (fruits, plants, seas), the eschatological (description of Hell then Paradise), and the divine (the eternal Face of Allah: وَيَبقَىٰ وَجهُ رَبِّكَ ذُو الجَلَالِ وَالإِكرَامِ — 55:27).',
