      question: 'What is the Tafseer of Surah al-Fatiha\'s phrase "الرَّحْمٰنِ الرَّحِيم" and what is the difference between the two names?',
      answer: 'Al-Rahman and al-Rahim are both derived from the root ر-ح-م (rahima — to show mercy). The distinction: (1) Al-Rahman (الرَّحْمٰن): the most intensive form — on the pattern فَعْلَان indicating fullness and completeness; refers to the divine mercy that encompasses ALL creation — believers and disbelievers, humans and animals, in this world: وَرَحمَتِي وَسِعَت كُلَّ شَيءٍ (7:156 — My mercy encompasses everything). It is a name exclusive to Allah — no human can be called al-Rahman. (2) Al-Rahim (الرَّحِيم): on the pattern فَعِيل indicating a stable, permanent quality that is continually expressed; refers to the special mercy for believers in the Hereafter: وَكَانَ بِالمُؤمِنِينَ رَحِيمًا (33:43 — He is ever merciful to the believers). This name can be applied to humans — the Prophet ﷺ called him rahim in Quran 9:128. The scholars summarize: al-Rahman is the mercy of provision in this world for all; al-Rahim is the mercy of reward in the Hereafter for believers specifically.',
