      answer: 'Al-Tafseer al-Tahlili (analytical/sequential tafseer) is the classical approach in which the mufassir proceeds through the Quran verse by verse (or ayah by ayah) from Surah al-Fatihah to Surah al-Nas, providing a comprehensive analysis of each verse. A complete tahlili tafseer typically addresses: (1) Al-Tafseer al-Lughawi — Arabic linguistic analysis: root meanings, grammar (irab), morphology (sarf), and rhetoric (balagha); (2) Asbab al-Nuzul — occasions of revelation if applicable; (3) Al-Munasabah — the connection between this verse and what precedes and follows; (4) Al-Ahkam al-Fiqhiyyah — legal rulings derived from the verse; (5) Al-Aqidah — theological implications; (6) Al-Fawaid — moral and practical lessons. The most comprehensive tahlili tafaseer: al-Tabari (transmitted narrations), al-Qurtubi (legal), al-Razi (theological/philosophical), Ibn Kathir (transmitted with authentication), al-Zamakhshari (linguistic/rhetorical), Ibn Ashur (rhetorical/maqasidi). Each represents a different emphasis within the same sequential method.',
